Description 
This is a Generalizability attempt on the Claim 4 claim (Study 2a) 
 
Consistent with the hypothesis, intimacy was higher in the attention condition (4.58 +/- .82) 
than in the no attention condition (2.82 +/- .79), t(27) = 5.91, p < .001, d = 2.20 
 
from Ohtsubo et al (2014). 
 
The statistical evidence is: intimacy was higher in the attention condition (4.58 +/- .82) than in 
the no attention condition (2.82 +/- .79), t(27) = 5.91, p < .001, d = 2.20 
 
 
In the generalizability study, the method for ensuring intimacy is modified to (hopefully) have a 
stronger induction of intimacy. In the Ohtsubo study, participants did not interact with the 
“other”; attention was indicated by a light changing color on the computer. In this 
generalizability study, attention will occur through an actual person (a RA) interacting through 
zoom (consistent with current COVID protocols). As such, this protocol should have more real 
world validity and applicability. 
